{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489546"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:20:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"688"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/688"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.13,0.13,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/688"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"688"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18305"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1138"},{"type":"tags","id":"7986"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35177"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents with a two-year history of a painless swelling behind his left ear lobe (Image). This appeared after he had ear piercing for a ring and the lump has been slowly increasing in size since then. He is otherwise healthy and never had any such lumps or skin problems before. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most effective treatment in terms of a low recurrence rate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical excision","Intralesional 5FU","Cryotherapy","Radiotherapy","Pressure dressing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis slowly growing painless swelling on the earlobe after an ear piercing is very suggestive of a keloid scar. All the listed options can be used for the treatment of keloid and all carry some risk of recurrence.  Keloid scars of ears do not share the same recurrence rate as keloid scars on other parts of the body.  They have much lower rate of recurrence after \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E.  The surgical excision is often combined together with compression earrings and/or serial intralesional steroid injection after surgical removal of the keloid scar to further reduce recurrence risk.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eused as adjuvant therapy 24 to 28 hours following excision and is shown to drastically reduce the recurrence rate. It is typically not used as a monotherapy. Caution should be used in patients less than 18 years of age and in vulnerable areas such as the head, neck, and breast as it carries an inherent risk of carcinogenesis.\u0026nbsp; \u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntralesional 5FU\u003C/strong\u003E is a chemotherapeutic agent which inhibits proliferation of cells within the scar tissue. It is less effective than surgical excision. The side-effects of 5-fluorouracil include pain, burning sensation, purpura formation, temporary hyperpigmentation, skin erythema, and ulceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Euses liquid nitrogen to cause cell damage and to affect the microvasculature, causing subsequent stasis, thrombosis, and transudation of fluid, which result in cell anoxia. Surgical excision has proved to be more effective than cryotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure dressing i\u003C/strong\u003Es often used after keloid surgery to reduce blood flow. This may stop a keloid from returning.  It is often used as an adjunctive treatment option.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Surgical excision has favourable outcome with low recurrence rate in the treatment of keloids."],"references":["Kim SW. Management of keloid scars: noninvasive and invasive treatments. Arch Plast Surg. 2021;48(2):149-157. doi:10.5999/aps.2020.01914."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18305"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"688"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19258"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19258"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e2b3b737-ba4e-4c1d-932d-0ca126f995c7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e2b3b737-ba4e-4c1d-932d-0ca126f995c7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/18305"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-20T21:40:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T16:15:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"688"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"posi